The MessageSummary.Envelope property only gets populated if you specify MessageSummaryItems.Envelope.

> What about Priority?

Yea, I guess I can see that as being a valuable header to have. When I originally added the `MessageSummaryItems.References` enum, I did not have an `IFetchRequest` and so there was no way to specify what headers you wanted (hence also why there is a `MessageSummaryItems.Headers`).

A better way to specify which headers you want would be to do something like this:

```csharp
// Fetch *ALL* headers (instead of Envelope, maybe because we don't trust the IMAP server's parsing and we want to do our own):
var fetchRequest = new FetchRequest (MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId | MessageSummaryItems.Flags) {
    Headers = HeaderSet.All
};
```

```csharp
// Fetch Envelope and References:
var fetchRequest = new FetchRequest (MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId | MessageSummaryItems.Envelope | MessageSummaryItems.Flags) {
    Headers = HeaderSet.References
};
```

```csharp
// Fetch Envelope, References, Importance, and *Priority:
var fetchRequest = new FetchRequest (MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId | MessageSummaryItems.Envelope | MessageSummaryItems.Flags) {
    Headers = new HeaderSet (new HeaderId[] {
        HeaderId.References,
        HeaderId.Importance,
        HeaderId.Priority,
        HeaderId.XPriority,
        HeaderId.XMSMailPriority
    })
};
```

The added bonus of the IFetchRequest is that you can also fetch the inverse of the headers you specify (e.g. `FETCH BODY[HEADERS.NOT (<list>)]`):

```csharp
// Fetch all of the headers except the Received headers
var fetchRequest = new FetchRequest (MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId | MessageSummaryItems.Envelope | MessageSummaryItems.Flags) {
    Headers = new HeaderSet (new HeaderId[] {
        HeaderId.Received
    }) {
        Exclude = true
    }
};
```

