Are you using ImapClient.GetFolders()?

When you use ImapClient.GetFolders(), it will list ALL folders and if you have tons of folders, that could cause the IMAP server to drop the connection (which is what it sounds like is happening to you).

This problem is made even worse with IMAP servers such as UW.IMAPd if some folders are symlinks that link back to other folders within the same folder structure because it creates an infinite loop of folders.

The way to get around this is to get 1 level of folders at a time like this:

```csharp
var toplevel = client.GetFolder (client.PersonalNamespaces[0]);
var firstLevel = toplevel.GetSubfolders (...);
foreach (var folder in firstLevel) {
    var secondLevel = folder.GetSubfolders (...);
}
```

And just recursively list the folders like that as far as you want to go.

If you aren't using ImapClient.GetFolders() or need further assistance, let me know.

What those errors mean is that .NET's SslStream implementation was unable to check the revocation status (I'm sure you figured that part out).

```csharp
client.CheckCertificateRevocation = false;
```

I would have expected the above code snippet to have worked, but I guess it didn't for you for some reason.

The next thing I would try, would be to try implementing your own certificate validation callback. Start with something like this:

```csharp
client.ServerCertificateValidationCallback = MyCertificateValidationCallback;
```

```csharp
static bool IsUnableToCheckRevocation (X509Chain chain)
{
    foreach (var status in chain.ChainStatus) {
        if (status.Status == X509ChainStatusFlags.NoError || status.Status == X509ChainStatusFlags.OfflineRevocation || status.Status == X509ChainStatusFlags.RevocationStatusUnknown)
            continue;

        return false;
    }

    return true;
}

bool MyCertificateValidationCallback (object sender, X509Certificate certificate, X509Chain chain, SslPolicyErrors sslPolicyErrors)
{
    const SslPolicyErrors mask = SslPolicyErrors.RemoteCertificateNotAvailable | SslPolicyErrors.RemoteCertificateNameMismatch;

    if (sslPolicyErrors == SslPolicyErrors.None)
        return true;

    if ((sslPolicyErrors & mask) == 0) {
        // At this point, all that is left is SslPolicyErrors.RemoteCertificateChainErrors

        // If the problem is a revocation check error, then ignore it.
        if (IsUnableToCheckRevocation (chain))
            return true;
    }

    return false;
}
```

FYI: For the Connect() method call, port 587 should use `SecureSocketOptions.StartTls` (or any value *other than* `SecureSocketOptions.SslOnConnect` - `SslOnConnect` should only be used with port 465).

