With any of the MailKit Smtp/Pop3/ImapClient classes, a socket is instantiated/connected in the `Connect` method and disconnected/disposed in the `Disconnect` method. The `Dispose` method on each of the Client classes will force a disconnect by calling `Disconnect (false)` but they will just kill the socket rather than sending a "LOGOUT" command, so I would definitely recommend calling `Disconnect (true)` before `Dispose` whether you use the `using(resource)` pattern or not.

The problem people get into with `HttpClient` is that they dispose the client way too aggressively, not giving the OS time to clean up the disconnected socket(s) before instantiating a new HttpClient and making the next request, e.g.:

```csharp
for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    using (var new HttpClient ()) {
        // make a request, process it, etc...
    }
}
```

This *can* also be a problem with MailKit. For example, if you have 1000 messages you want to send, I would recommend reusing the same SmtpClient instance like this:

```csharp
using (var client = new SmtpClient ()) {
    client.Connect ("smtp.server.com", 587, SecureSocketOptions.StartTls);
    client.Authenticate ("username", "password");

    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
        client.Send (messages[i]);
    }

    client.Disconnect (true);
}
```

You can check if the POP3 server supports APOP using the following check:

```csharp
if (client.Capabilities.HasFlag (Pop3Capabilities.Apop))
```

You can check if the POP3 server supports the USER/PASS set of login commands using the following check:

```csharp
if (client.Capabilities.HasFlag (Pop3Capabilities.User))
```

If the POP3 server supports APOP, APOP authentication will be used in the Authenticate() method.

To disable it, do this:

```csharp
client.Capabilities &= ~Pop3Capabilities.Apop;
```

If the POP3 server supports *any* SASL mechanisms that MailKit supports, then MailKit will attempt to use the SASL mechanisms *first* and only fall back to `USER`/`PASS` if they fail.

To avoid attempting to login using a SASL mechanism, disable them *after* Connect() using:

```csharp
client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove ("PLAIN");
client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove ("LOGIN");
client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove ("CRAM-MD5");
client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove ("DIGEST-MD5");
// etc...
```

-or-

```csharp
client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Clear ();
```

Why do you need MailKit's SmtpClient to be thread safe?

You guys are being ridiculous.

Is List<T> thread safe?

Did you ever consider just doing your own locking? It's so simple to do:
```csharp
lock (client.SyncRoot) {
    client.Send (message);
}
```
Now you have thread safety.

The following basically works with `private SemaphoreSlim clientLock = new SemaphoreSlim(1, 1);`

```csharp
await clientLock.WaitAsync(token);
try
{
    await client.SendAsync(message, token, progress);
}
finally
{
    clientLock.Release();
}
```

However, you still need to be careful with any other code that is disconnecting or disposing the client but also avoiding excessive locking. For example, I call `NoOp()` before using the client to ensure it is still connected but if this fails, I disconnect the client so it gets removed and not used any more but of course, various threads could already have got through the `Connected` check and are mid-way through `SendAsync()` when this happens and instead of getting a nice error, we get the random NullReferenceException, understandable but not great.

I need to spend more time carefully locking some more scenarios.

