Your second implementation has a few issues. One of the things you need to keep in mind when using anonymous delegates is that the variables that you capture when creating those delegates are snapshots in time.

In other words, in your second implementation, the `done` token source is a snapshot of the first instance. It doesn't get updated when you create new CancellationTokenSources later, so your `CountChanged` event handler will continue to cancel the very first instance over and over again.

You need to make the `done` token source truly global (or, at least, global to a class that this code is all part of).

To handle reconnections, that's easy.

Just have a method that checks that the client is connected/authenticated, and if not, reconnects/re-authenticates.

```csharp
void ReconnectIfNeeded ()
{
    if (!client.IsConnected)
        client.Connect ("host", 993, true);

    if (!client.IsAuthenticated)
        client.Authenticate ("username", "password");
}
```

Then, to use it, do this:

```csharp
IList<IMessageSummary> fetched;

do {
    try {
        fetched = client.Inbox.Fetch (0, -1, MessageSummaryItems.Full | MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId);
        break;
    } catch (ImapProtocolException) {
        ReconnectIfNeeded ();
    } catch (IOException) {
        ReconnectIfNeeded ();
    }
} while (true);

foreach (var message in fetched) {
    Console.WriteLine("Subject: {0}", message.Envelope.Subject);
}
