If all you want is the UID of the most recent message in the folder, there's a few ways to do that.

As @ekalchev illustrated, you can do that using the Fetch() method:

```csharp
var summary = folder.Fetch (folder.Count - 1, folder.Count - 1, MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId).FirstOrDefault ();
var latestUid = summary != null ? summary.UniqueId : UniqueId.Invalid;
```

Note above that you need to pass `MessageSummaryItems.UniqueId` to the Fetch() method.

Another way is to use the Search() method:

```csharp
var all = folder.Search (SearchQuery.All);
var latestUid = all[all.Count - 1];
```

If your server supports `ImapCapabilities.SearchResults`, you can use the following approach:

```csharp
var results = folder.Search (SearchOptions.Max, SearchQuery.All);
var latestUid = results.Max.Value;
```

My recommendation would be to use the Fetch() method as I think it'll be cheaper for the server to calculate *and* return a minimum amount of data over the network connection (technically, the SearchResults option is less network traffic, but fewer servers will support this feature and the ones that do might not implement it as efficiently as it could be done).

The one caveat with the Fetch() approach is that another client could delete that last message before you get a chance to make that Fetch query, so you'll need to handle cases where it returns nothing.

