I would recommend keeping the ImapClient reference and not disposing it after each minor usage.

Most likely this will mean you'll have to stop using it in a `using` statement and instead have some sort of application-level reference to the ImapClient so that you can reuse them over and over again.

You will also need to keep the connection alive by invoking client.NoOp() every once in a while (I would recommend calling NoOp() every 5-10 minutes or so).

For SMTP, I would recommend queueing a bunch of messages to send and then sending all of them like this:

```csharp
using (var client = new SmtpClient ()) {
    client.Connect (.....);
    client.Authenticate (....);

    for (int i = 0; i < messages.Count; i++)
        client.Send (messages[i]);

    client.Disconnect (true);
}
```

