comments.body:
The way that cancellation works is that if a command is already in progress, it has to drop the connection (there's no other way).

The convention for doing cancellation should probably look a bit like this from your perspective:

```csharp
try {
    client.DoSomethingAsync (..., cancellationToken);
} catch (OperationCanceledException) {
    if (!client.IsConnected) {
        Reconnect ();
    }
}
```

I should note that the `ImapEngine` always checks cancelation state *before* issuing the command as well, so it's possible that the connection is not dropped if the command hasn't been sent yet, so you should always check `client.IsConnected`.

